    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local intent</strong> is the underlying goal a searcher has to find a business, service, or product within a specific geographic area. When Google detects local intent in a query — through location names, "near me" phrases, or GPS-based inference — it restructures the search results page to prioritise the Local Pack, map listings, direction links, and click-to-call buttons over standard blue-link results.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Search share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~46% of all Google searches</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Conversion signal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">76% visit in 1 day (mobile)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Understanding local intent is the starting point for every local SEO decision. If a keyword carries local intent, you need a Google Business Profile and local landing pages — not just a blog post. Miss this and you're optimising the wrong assets for the wrong result type.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is local intent?</h2>
        <p>Local intent is a classification of search query behaviour that Google uses to decide what type of results to show. It sits within Google's broader search intent framework alongside informational intent (research), navigational intent (finding a specific site), and transactional intent (buying something).</p>
        <p>Local intent queries share one characteristic: the searcher wants something nearby. That "nearby" can be:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Explicitly stated</strong> — the query names a location: "dentist Chicago," "plumber near me," "restaurants in Shoreditch"</li>
          <li><strong>Implicitly understood</strong> — the query implies local need without naming a location: "emergency plumber," "dentist open Saturday," "coffee shop," "nail salon appointment"</li>
        </ul>
        <p>When Google classifies a query as having local intent, it activates local SERP features including the Local Pack (map + 3 business listings), knowledge panels for specific businesses, direction links, click-to-call buttons, hours of operation, and review star ratings.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The 46% figure — what it means</div>
          <p>Google has stated that <strong>46% of all searches have local intent</strong>. For a business running paid or organic search, this means nearly half the queries relevant to your category are being filtered through Google's local ranking algorithm — not the standard organic algorithm. The two systems require different optimisation strategies.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local intent matters for businesses</h2>
        <p>Local intent is one of the highest-converting search categories because it represents active purchase or visit intent. The data is unambiguous:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>76% of local mobile searches result in a business visit within 24 hours</strong> (Google internal data). Compare this to informational searches, where purchase decisions can take weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Local Pack dominates clicks.</strong> Studies show the Local Pack (positions 1-3 in local results) captures 44% of clicks for local intent queries. Being out of the Pack entirely means missing the majority of traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Conversion rates for local intent traffic are 2-5x higher</strong> than generic organic traffic because the user is actively looking for a nearby provider right now.</li>
          <li><strong>Local intent triggers rich SERP features</strong> — review stars, photos, click-to-call — that pre-qualify leads before they visit your site, improving the quality of contacts you receive.</li>
          <li><strong>Competition is geographically bounded.</strong> You're not competing with every plumber globally — only those within 5-10 miles. This makes local intent keywords more winnable than national terms for SMBs.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google detects local intent</h2>
        <p>Google uses machine learning trained on billions of search-click patterns to classify query intent in real time. The local intent detection pipeline works across three input types:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Query text analysis.</strong> Keywords that include city names, postcodes, neighbourhood names, "near me," "close to," or "open now" are immediately flagged as explicit local intent. Google's NLP systems parse these signals within milliseconds of the query being submitted.</li>
          <li><strong>Searcher location data.</strong> For mobile users, Google uses GPS coordinates from the device. For desktop users, Google uses IP-based location inference. A search for "coffee shop" from a device in Austin, Texas, activates local intent even without any location word in the query — because Google knows the user is in Austin.</li>
          <li><strong>Historical query patterns.</strong> Google maintains click-through data at the keyword level. If "coffee shop" has historically generated high click rates on Local Pack results (versus clicking blue organic links), it is classified as carrying implicit local intent regardless of how vague the query text is.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Explicit vs implicit local intent — key differences</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Definition</th><th>Query examples</th><th>Google's response</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Explicit local intent</strong></td>
                <td>Query names a location directly</td>
                <td>"plumber in Denver," "pizza Chicago," "dentist near me"</td>
                <td>Full Local Pack + map at top of SERP</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Implicit local intent</strong></td>
                <td>Query implies locality from context or service type</td>
                <td>"emergency plumber," "coffee shop," "haircut appointment"</td>
                <td>Local Pack if user's GPS confirms local context</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>No local intent</strong></td>
                <td>Informational or non-geographic query</td>
                <td>"how to fix a leaky pipe," "best pizza recipe," "dentistry degree"</td>
                <td>Standard organic results — no Local Pack</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real local intent examples</h2>
        <p>Here are three search scenarios that illustrate how local intent works in practice.</p>

        <h3>1. Explicit local intent — "Italian restaurant San Francisco"</h3>
        <p>A user in New York searches "Italian restaurant San Francisco" before a trip. Google detects the named city and activates full local intent: the SERP shows a Local Pack with map centred on San Francisco, business listings with star ratings, photos, and menus, followed by organic results (restaurant review sites, food blogs). The user clicks through the Local Finder to compare 8 restaurants.</p>

        <h3>2. Implicit local intent — "dentist open Saturday"</h3>
        <p>A user in suburban Chicago searches "dentist open Saturday." No city name is mentioned. Google uses the user's GPS location to infer local intent and shows a Local Pack of nearby dentists with Saturday hours marked as "Open." Organic results appear below, but the Local Pack captures 60-70% of clicks for this type of query.</p>

        <h3>3. No local intent — "how to make pasta"</h3>
        <p>A user searches "how to make pasta." Google classifies this as informational intent with no local component — it returns recipe sites, YouTube videos, and food blogs. Even if you run an Italian restaurant with a pasta-making class, this query will not show your Local Pack listing. A blog post on your site targeting this keyword is the correct asset, not your GBP.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local intent vs search intent — how they relate</h2>
        <p>Local intent is a sub-type of search intent, not a separate category. Google classifies every query by primary intent before applying local signals. Understanding the relationship determines which assets you build:</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>When local intent applies — build these</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Optimised Google Business Profile</li>
              <li>Location-specific landing pages</li>
              <li>LocalBusiness schema markup</li>
              <li>Citation profile across directories</li>
              <li>Review velocity strategy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>When local intent doesn't apply — build these</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Blog posts targeting informational queries</li>
              <li>How-to guides and tutorials</li>
              <li>Industry research and data reports</li>
              <li>Comparison pages for product decisions</li>
              <li>FAQ pages answering generic questions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for ranking in local intent searches</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Identify which of your target keywords have local intent before building content.</strong> Search each keyword manually or use Semrush's intent filter. Build a GBP-first strategy for local intent keywords, content-first for informational ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimise your GBP primary category to match the highest-volume local intent query for your business.</strong> If "emergency plumber" is your biggest local intent keyword, your primary GBP category should be "Emergency Plumber" not just "Plumber."</li>
          <li><strong>Build location-specific landing pages with unique content.</strong> If you serve multiple cities, create a separate page for each with unique service descriptions, local testimonials, and the city name in the H1, title tag, and URL. Thin location pages with copied text are penalised.</li>
          <li><strong>Use LocalBusiness schema markup on every location page.</strong> Include name, address, phone, opening hours, geo coordinates, and price range. This structured data helps Google correctly attribute your location-specific content to the right geographic area.</li>
          <li><strong>Target near-me keyword variants explicitly in your GBP services and website copy.</strong> "Plumber near me" has millions of monthly searches across all locations combined. Optimising GBP services descriptions and FAQ sections to answer "near me" phrasing captures this implicit demand.</li>
          <li><strong>Track local intent keywords separately from national keywords.</strong> Use a rank tracker that reports Local Pack position (not just organic position). A keyword where you rank #5 organically but #1 in Local Pack is performing far better than the organic rank implies.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — building blog posts for local intent keywords</div>
          <p>A common error is writing a blog post targeting "plumber Denver" because it has search volume. But "plumber Denver" has local intent — Google shows a Local Pack, not a list of blog posts. Your GBP and location landing page rank for this keyword, not your blog. Blog posts belong to informational local intent queries like "when do pipes freeze in Denver" or "how much does plumbing cost in Denver."</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local intent mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Conflating local intent with transactional intent.</strong> A query like "buy plumbing parts Denver" is both transactional and local — it requires an ecommerce page with local schema, not just a GBP listing. Know which sub-intent applies.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring implicit local intent keywords.</strong> Optimising only for "near me" phrases misses the majority of local intent traffic, which arrives via implicit queries like "urgent care" or "locksmith" without any location word.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the same landing page for multiple cities.</strong> Serving a generic "plumber in [city]" template with only the city name swapped triggers Google's thin-content filters and ranks poorly for local intent queries in each market.</li>
          <li><strong>Not verifying local intent with an actual SERP check.</strong> Keyword research tools are not always accurate about intent classification. Always manually search your target keywords to confirm whether Google shows a Local Pack.</li>
          <li><strong>Running Google Ads for local intent keywords without location targeting enabled.</strong> Without location targeting, your budget is spread nationally. Enable radius or city targeting to match the local intent signal Google detects in the query.</li>
        </ul>

